findings.detail:
DOM-1(b) derives in_bounds(s,i) for off<=i<off+n from a passed `check ile(<off+n>, len(s))`, then uses it to elide the [OP-4]/LOAD-1 bounds trap. The draft NAMES the overflow risk ('an overflowing off+n that wrapped could forge an in-bounds fact') and says the sum 'must be proven non-overflowing (spelled .checked or a proven range).' But that obligation is neither well-formed nor dischargeable as drafted: (i) the canonical producer `iadd.checked-proven` is not an OP-1 row, and a real `iadd.checked<u64>` returns Result<u64,Overflow> (spec line 205), which cannot be an operand of `ile<u64>` (needs u64) -- so the ONLY well-typed u64 sum producers are `iadd.wrap` (silently wraps) and `iadd.trap`; (ii) DOM-1 is explicitly the FIRST slice of the range vocabulary, so there is no existing range-fact to 'prove a range' with -- the non-overflow discharge has no mechanism; (iii) no rule text rejects the `.wrap` producer. Concrete forge (C8 validated-view shape, off parsed from input):

  fn load_field['r](s: slice<'r,u8>, off: u64) -> own u16 reads('r), traps {
    let n: own u64 = len<u8>(s);
    let sum: own u64 = iadd.wrap<u64>(off, 2_u64);   // total, pure, LEGAL
    check ile<u64>(sum, n) else trap "range";        // OP-5 producer, retained
    let v: own u16 = load_le_u16(s, off);            // window discharges the trap
    return v;
  }
  // call load_field(s, 18446744073709551615) with n>=1:
  //   sum = wrap(2^64-1 + 2) = 1 ; check ile(1, n) PASSES (retained check is vacuous)
  //   DOM-1 asserts in_bounds(s, 2^64-1); load reads 2 bytes at base+2^64-1 -> OOB

The retained OP-5 check does not save this: it compares the wrapped sum (1<=n) and passes; the forged fact then elides a DIFFERENT check (the load/index bounds). This is the exact bounds-elision-forgery class the standing rule requires be closed before adoption.

DOM-1's invalidator set is a CLOSED list of TABLE OPS ('grow, reserve, clear, truncate, a resizing store'); a user-fn call is not in it. SEQ-6 states structure facts (LEN/CAP/SLACK/INB) are 'killed only as rows state,' and facts are per-binding (CAT-2). No rule kills the CALLER's window/pow2 fact at a call that receives the place by &uniq and resizes it internally -- the kill fires on the callee's own binding, not the caller's. Concrete UAF (both DOM-1 forms; here (b)):

  fn steal['e](x: &uniq 'e seq<u8,0>) -> own unit writes('e) {
    let taken: own seq<u8,0> = seq_take_all(x); // x -> empty inline (cap 0, heap store moved out and dropped)
    return unit;
  }
  fn use_it(off: u64) -> own u8 allocates(heap), traps {
    region 'e {
      let s: own seq<u8,0> = seq_with_cap<u8,0>(128_u64);
      // ... push to len 100 ...
      let n: own u64 = seq_len(&'e s);                 // 100
      let sum: own u64 = iadd.trap<u64>(off, 1_u64);
      check ile<u64>(sum, n) else trap "range";        // window: in_bounds(s, off) for off<=99
      steal<'e>(x: &uniq 'e s);                         // s reset to empty inline, backing freed
      region 'g { let r: &'g u8 = seq_get<'g>(s: &'g s, i: off);  // INB(s,off) survived the call -> bounds ELIDED
                  let b: own u8 = deref(r); return b; } // OOB/UAF read of the freed store when off in [1,99]
    }
  }

seq_take_all's own kill column supersedes INB(s,*) -- but on x inside steal, never propagated back to s in use_it. Both DOM-1 named consumers (C2 buffer<u64>, C8 buffer<u8>/slice) use NON-resizable backing and never hit this, which is why the cards do not expose it; the general rule text (which lists seq resizers as invalidators) invites it. This is a FATAL-class UAF; certainty is contingent only on whether the checker's (unspecified) fact engine conservatively kills facts at &uniq-passing calls -- the delta states neither that it does nor a restriction, so it is unclosed.
